The goal of this change is to provide a mechanism for external contributors to leverage the power of Roslyn. One example being extension developers need a way to access Roslyn in a performant way. This PR utilizes LSP to expose a simple handler interface to external developers. 

What this entails..
1. External calls make an LSP request to _extensions/registerExtension_ and provide the assembly path and full type name of the external handler. 
2. ExtensionRegistrationHandler.cs loads the DLL and uses reflection to get the IExtensionMethodHandler
3. The IExtensionMethodHandler is then wrapped in the ExtensionMethodHandlerWrapper, which can be loaded by the HandlerProvider
4. TODO: The HandlerProvider adds the ExtensionMethodHandlerWrapper to its handler map and calls SetupRequestDispatcher to add the RPC method.

Practically speaking, the external extension writer will implement a handler similar to this...
```
    [Method("beccaExtension/myExampleHandler")]
    internal class BeccaExtension : ExtensionMethodHandler<string, string>
    {
        public override Task<string> HandleRequestAsync(string request, SimpleRequestContext context, CancellationToken cancellationToken)
        {
            return Task.FromResult("Becca extension: Hello from the external code! Code word is: " + request);
        }
    }
```

And to register the handler, they'll send an LSP request: 
```
type: "extensions/registerExtension"
request: 
{
assemblyPath : ... 
typeFullName: "BeccaExtension"
}
```

Then, to execute BeccaExtension.HandleRequestAsync, they will need to send an LSP request: 
```
type: "beccaExtension/myExampleHandler"
request: 
{
// Extension request object 
}
```
